Linux signals set signals in the dest, and then hunt to see if the thread is
running, needs to be unblocked, whether blocking can be interrupted, etc.  When
a thread is switched to, it checks the mask to see if it should handle signals
before returning.



	******************* pi / better m/futexes *******************

Word has ThreadID in upper bits.  Lower bits have state information.

PIFutexWait -- like normal, uses upper bits of val as threadid

PIFutexHandoff(u32_t *ptr, u32_t unlocked_val) -- Wakes best priority thread
putting in that threadid, or writes unlocked_val if no other threads are
waiting.


Keep on boosting holder priority while waiting.  Unlock happens in correct 
priority order.  New threads coming in will boost holder prio, then get 
resumed in right order.

TBD: following the blocked chain?


Normal Futex Pass:

States:
	* Unlocked
	* Locked, no waiters
	* Locked + Waiters (maybe)
	* Pass


Alternative:
	Field 0:
		* Locked
		* Unlocked
		* Pass
	Field 1:
		* n_waiters


If we come into a mutex and we see pass, we need to block.

Pass state only valid if threads are waiting and we can wake up.
Two ways to know this:
	* Count of waiters (maybe?)
	* Try and wake one thread, if zero returned, set to normal 
		unlocked (and then wait just to be sure)




	******************** Preemption Disable *****************

Clear IE bit in SSR.  Blocking still allowed.  Raise priority; select
someone else as lowprio.








	******************** Multilevel Translations ************

Guest maps Virtual -> Intermediate

But... we'll probably need to support KVM/XEN/VMWARE.

So, we will have

Virtual -> Intermediate -> Intermediate -> Physical
     (Linux)        (VMWare)           (h2)


And, just because it's awesome, it would be nice to have:

Virtual -> Intermediate -> Intermediate -> Intermediate -> Physical


Virtual is obviously what registers hold.

Physical is obviously what the actual machine holds.

TLB needs to translate Virtual -> Physical.

Thus, my recommendation is that STLB also holds Virtual -> Physical

However, every time you walk a page table, say at the Linux level, every lookup
is really a virtual address from some other level.

So let's just make it a real virtual address.

Each address space maps a set of Input addresses to a set of Output addresses.
We can have an "Output ASID".  If this ASID is something special (-1 or 0 or
something), the output address is a physical address and we are done.

If the "Output ASID" is not the special value, we just need to continue looking
up the translation, but now we just recurse into the same algorithm with a new ASID. 

The STLB (or indeed, TLB) can be used at any time while walking any structure
to convert any non-physical address to a physical one.

Using the real TLB might be very interesting, the TLB walk code could just
switch to the target ASID and use virtual loads/stores... if there's a TLB miss
then the nested TLB miss handler would switch to the target ASID and get *that*
fault fixed up, etc.  Would require lots of thinking about the right way to
nest, but it isn't too inelegant.


	**************** Multilevel Permissions / DSM ************

At some level, someone is going to figure out the DSM.  

It's probably easiest to do this at the highest level possible... and that
should probably be how we research this; get KVM working on each node and
then have all the KVM hosts to implement the protocol for their guests.

OTOH, it might be simpler if we could do it at the lowest level.

Doing the DSM dance fundimentally means removing permissions that the guest
environments think they have.  This might be write permissions (in the case of
shared pages), or it might be read permissions (if the page is not shared
to the current coherence domain).  That means that whatever translations might
cache the permissions, we need to invalidate the cache.  And as we look up 
V->P, we need the last level to include the DSM permissions in addition to 
whatever other policy we might have.


